data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code has **four** Thread.Abort patterns that all break on .NET 8 (`PlatformNotSupportedException` / `SYSLIB0006`):

| Pattern Found | Location | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (_running)` | `CancellationToken` |
| **ThreadAbortException catch** | `catch` block with rollback | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | Keeps thread alive after abort | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |
| **Blocking call interruption** | `GetNextItem()` may block | `token.WaitHandle` / async overloads |

### Key pitfalls for this specific code

1. **`GetNextItem()` blocks** — `CancellationToken` won't interrupt a blocking synchronous call. You must pass the token into `GetNextItem()` or replace it with an async alternative, otherwise `Stop()` hangs.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort` loop continuation** — The old code caught the abort, rolled back, then *continued* the loop. With cooperative cancellation you check `token.IsCancellationRequested` after rollback and decide whether to continue or exit.
3. **`volatile bool _running`** — Redundant once you switch to `CancellationToken`; the token already provides thread-safe signaling.
4. **`CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed** — Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks.

### Migrated code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable.
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — roll back partial work,
                // then let the loop condition exit naturally.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish.
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop — means GetNextItem or ProcessItem
            // isn't honoring the token. Log a warning; you cannot
            // force-kill a managed thread in .NET 8.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| Old (.NET Framework) | New (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Thread-safe, composable, passes through call chains |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal instead of preemptive kill |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` guard avoids catching unrelated OCEs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | Loop naturally re-evaluates `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` + alive check | `_workerThread.Join(2s)` | Blocks until thread exits or timeout — no busy wait |
| *(nothing)* | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed |

### Critical: make `GetNextItem` cancellable

The old code relied on `Thread.Abort` to interrupt `GetNextItem()` when it was blocked. **Cancellation tokens don't interrupt blocking calls.** You must update `GetNextItem`:

```csharp
// If it blocks on a queue, use BlockingCollection<T>:
private BlockingCollection<WorkItem> _queue = new();

private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}

// If it blocks on a WaitHandle/ManualResetEvent:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(
        new[] { _dataReady, token.WaitHandle });
    if (index == 1)
        throw new OperationCanceledException(token);
    return DequeueItem();
}

// If it blocks on Thread.Sleep:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(pollInterval); // wakes on cancel
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return DequeueItem();
}
```

If `GetNextItem` calls unmodifiable code that truly blocks, your only option is to move that work to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill` as the last resort — there is no managed-thread equivalent of `Thread.Abort` in .NET 8.
